<!--hand01topleft10--><!--hand01topright11-->
<lb/><p rend="right">Kongone 28 February</p>
<lb/><p rend="right">1860.</p>
<lb/><p rend="left">My Dear Nannie</p>
<lb/><p>I send this home 
<lb/>By <persName>M<hi rend="sup"><hi rend="underline">r</hi></hi> Rae</persName> our Engineer whom 
<lb/>probably you may see. I send 
<lb/>at the same time a box with 
<lb/>a few objects of natural history 
<lb/>for <persName>Robert</persName> and <persName>Thomas</persName>
<lb/>and a few rings for you 
<lb/>one is a lip ring and if 
<lb/>you like to wear it as 
<lb/>the women up the <placeName>Shire</placeName>
<lb/>do <persName>M<hi rend="sup"><hi rend="underline">r</hi></hi> Rae</persName> will shew you 
<lb/>how. I bought it and the 
<lb/>woman took it out of a 
<lb/>hole in her lip &amp; gave it 

	<pb n="0002" facs="liv_001543_0002"/><!--pb/@n='12r'--> 
<lb/><!--hand0112-->very sorry I thought to part with 
<lb/>a thing that made her so "brave." 
<lb/>O Dear me, our <persName>Nannie</persName> will 
<lb/>soon be so tall she wont know 
<lb/>when her toes are cold. I hear 
<lb/>nothing from <persName>Mamma</persName> but 
<lb/>hope soon to find letters in a 
<lb/>mail bag which was lost in 
<lb/>the sea and found. <persName>Uncle 
<lb/>Charles</persName> is here and well. If fond 
<lb/>of music you might learn on 
<lb/>an instrument <persName>M<hi rend="sup"><hi rend="underline">r</hi></hi> Rae</persName> will 
<lb/>take home. The Lord bless 
<lb/>and keep you from all 
<lb/>evil. 
<lb/><!--autograph cut off end of letter--></p>
			
